obj_root_law_sections_1_content:
  string
  line 1
  line `THE BENGA L EMBANKMENT ACT, 185 5`
  line `A CT N O. X XXI I OF 185 5`
  line `[ Passed on the 30 th November, 185 5.]`
  line `1. Repeal Bengal R. 6, 1806 and B.R. 11, 1829.`
  line `2. Defines what embankments are within the Act.`
  line `3. 4. Embankments to be under superintendent of embankments; to whom powers are given to take`
  line `charge, &c. change, &c. and enlarge &c. the embankments.`
  line `5. Superintendent to give notice to Collector before he removes, changes or enlarges and embankment;`
  line `who (cl. 2,) shall make proclamation; (cl.3,) hear objections, and pass orders if Collector and`
  line `Superintendent agree: and ( cl.4, ) orders appealable: ( cl.5 ) subject to appeal, ord ers to be final.`
  line `6. Proprietors bound to maintain embankments, to pay for their mainten ance, when.`
  line `7. Entitles persons sustaining damage from alterations, to compensation from Collector, and by civil`
  line `action, and amount in admitted claims to be settled by arbitration; and (cl. 2,) provides for appointment of`
  line `arbitrators: (cl. 3) when there are several claimants: and (cl. 4,) for umpire, and (cl. 5,) for case of refusal`
  line `of arbitrator to act, &c.; and (cl. 6,) empowers Collector to enforce attendance of arbitrators; and (cl. 7,)`
  line `on default of arbitration may appoint new arbitrators; and (cl. 8,) to conduct the arbitration; (cl. 9.) and`
  line `award, and proceedings to be deposited in his office; and (cl. 10, ) may defer payment in certain cases; and`
  line `(cl. 11,) award to be set aside only on grounds of corruption, &c. and (cl. 12,) gives costs to Government;`
  line `and (cl. 13,) fixes a measure of compensation; but (cl. 14,) excepts from these provisions certain cases of`
  line compensation.
  line `8. Provides for making sluices for landholders in embankments; (cl. 2,) officer to report on the proposed`
  line `work; but (cl. 3,) applicant to pay the expense.`
  line `9. Sluices to be opened only by public officer, &c.`
  line `10. Authorizes the making of tempo rary water - courses, &c. through embankment.`
  line `11. Provides for specif ications, &c. of works expense of which belongs to Zemindars, &c. and (cl. 2,)`
  line `provides for accounts being kept.`
  line `12. Authorize Sup. t o report to Collector houses, &c. the removal of which he deems necessary; and`
  line `(cl. 2,) Collector to give notice to interested parties; and (cl. 3, 4 and 5,) jury to ascertain the value and`
  line `make award.`
  line `13, 14. After award Collector to give notice to parties concerned: and (14) in their default houses, &c.`
  line `May be removed by Collector.`
  line `15, 16,17. Establishes penalty for obstructing the removal of houses, &c. and (16) for cutting, &c.`
  line `ambankments; and (17) for damaging embankments by other means.`
  line `18. Gives jurisdiction under the Act to Deputy and Assistant Magistates.`
  line `19. Empowers Darogahs to inquire.`
  line `20. Orders of Magistrate, &c. appealable.`
  line `21. Interpretation clause.`
  line `An Act relating to E mbankments.`
  line `Preamble. - Whereas the Regulations now in force for the maintenance embankments in the T erritories`
  line `under the Government of the Lieutenant - Governor of Bengal, have been found ineffectual for the intended`
  line `purposes thereof, and whereas it is desirable that provision should be made for the better supervision and`
  line `protection of the same it is enacted as follows:`
obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_2:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-2
  sectionNo (2)
  orderNo 2
  title `Page 2`
  content obj_root_law_sections_2_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes
  sourcePage 2
obj_root_law_sections_2_content:
  string
  line 2
  line `I. Regulations Repealed. — Regulation VI. of 1806 and Regulation XI. of 1829, so far as they relate`
  line `to the said Territories, are hereby repealed, except so far as they repeal the whole or part of any other`
  line `Regulation, and except as to acts done, offences committed, and liabilities incurred before the passing of`
  line `this Act.`
  line `II. What is a public embankment within this Act. — The word “ embankment ” in this Act means an`
  line `e mbankment for the purpose of excluding or retaining water; and every embankment which is now kept up,`
  line `or may hereafter be kept up, by the officers of the Government, at the expense either of Government or of`
  line `any private person, is a public embankment within the meaning hereof.`
  line `III. Who to have superintendence of p ublic embankments. — The Superintendence of the public`
  line `embankments shall be entrusted, subject to the general orders Government, to an O fficer who shall be`
  line `called the Superintendent of Embankme nts.`
  line `IV. Clause 1. — Superintendent may take c harge of any embankment which connecting public`
  line `embankments, &c. — The Superintendent of Embankments may cause any Embankment which connects`
  line `public embankments, or forms by junction with them part of a line of embankments, or is necessary for the`
  line `protection of the neighbouring country, to be taken charge of and kept up by the officers of the Crown.`
  line `Clause 2. — And r emov e private embankment endangering a public embankment. — He may also`
  line `cause any private embankment, which endangers the stability of a public embankment, or obstructs the`
  line `beneficial drainage of the country, to be removed.`
  line `Clause 3. — And Chang e line of any public embankment or mak e a new embankment. — He may`
  line `also, when necessary, cha n ge the line of any public embankment, or make a new embankment.`
  line `Clause 4. — And e nlarging embankment, etc. — He may also enlarge any public embankment, and do`
  line `all acts necessary and proper for the maintenance thereof.`
  line `VI. Clause 1. — Before taking charge of private embankments, &c. Superintendent to give notice to`
  line `Collector, who shall issue a proclamation. — Before the Superintendent shall cause any of the works`
  line `mentioned in the first three clauses of the next preceding S ection to be executed, he shall give notice in`
  line `writing to the Collector of the district of his intention so to do. Upon the receipt of such notice, the Collector`
  line `shall cause a proclamation to be issued, incorporating the substance of the notice, and calling upon all`
  line `pe rsons interested, who may be desirous of showing cause against the execution of such works, to appear`
  line `before him on a certain day to be named therein.`
  line `Clause 2. — Publication of proclamation. — The proclamation shall be published by affixing the same`
  line `in the C utcherry of the Collector, the M al C utcherry (if any) of the estate on which the works are intended`
  line `to be executed, and on some conspicuous spot in the neighbourhood thereof. The proclamation shall be`
  line `published not less than fifteen days before the day appointed for hearing the parties interested.`
  line `Clause 3. — Procedure on appearance of parties. — The Collector shall hear the objections of any`
  line `parties who may appear, and, after recording any evidence which they may adduce, shall communicate the`
  line `objections that may be made, together with his opinion thereon, to the Superintendent of Embankments. If`
  line `the Superintendent agrees in opinion with the Collector, he shall pass an order accordingly. If he differ from`
  line `the Collector, the case shall be referred to the Commissioner of Revenue, who shall pass such orders thereon`
  line `as he may deem fit.`
  line `Clause 4. — Appeal from orders of Superintendent and Commissioner of Revenue. — Every such`
  line `order passed by the Superintendent shall be appealable to the Commissioner of Revenue, and every order`
  line `of the Commissioner shall be appealable to the Board of Revenue; but no appeal shall lie against any order`
  line `passed under this section, unless the same be presented within one month form the date of the order.`
  line `Clause 5. — Order not open to revision by C ivil C ourt. — Subject to the right of appeal above -`
  line `mentioned and to the orders and control of Government, every order passed under this S ection shall be final`
  line `and shall not be open to revision by any Civil Court, and shall be conclusive as to the necessity of any`
  line `works ordered to be executed.`
  line `VI. M aint enance of private embankments taken charge of by the O fficers of Government. —`
  line `( 1 ) Whenever the Superintendent of Embankments shall hereafter cause an embankment, which any person`
  line `is bound to keep up, to be taken charge of by the officers of Government, the expense of keeping up such`
  line `embankment shall be charge to such person, Provided th at the amount so charged shall not exceed the`
obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_3:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-3
  sectionNo (3)
  orderNo 3
  title `Page 3`
  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  sourcePage 3
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line 3
  line `reasonable expenses of keeping up an embankment in the size and description, which such person was`
  line `bound to keep up, notwithstanding the embankment shall have been enlarged or improved by the officers`
  line `of Govern ment.`
  line `VII. Clause 1. — Compensation for damages sustained under this Act. — When the Superintendent`
  line `of Embankments shall enlarge or change the line of any embankment, or make a new embankment, or`
  line `cause an embankment to be removed, any person sustaining damages thereby, who, but for the passing of`
  line `this Act, would be entitled to c ompensation, may prefer his claim for such compensation to the Collector`
  line `of the D istrict, at any time within twelve months after the execution of the work by which he is endamaged,`
  line `and the Collector thereupon shall report the case for the orders of the superior Revenue authorities. If the`
  line `claim be rejected, the claimant shall not be deprived, by reason of this Act, of any right which he might`
  line `otherwise have had, to recover such compensation by a civil action; but such action shall not lie, unless the`
  line `cla imant shall have first preferred his claim to the Collector within the period above mentioned, nor unless`
  line `the suit be brought within a period of one year after notice to the claimant of its rejection. If the claim for`
  line `compensation be admitted by the Revenu e authorities, and the amount of compensation cannot be agreed`
  line `upon, the same shall be settled by arbitration, in the manner hereinafter provided, and in no other manner,`
  line `unless by the consent of the claimant and of the superior Revenue authorities.`
  line `Clause 2. — Appointment of arbitrator. — Unless the Collector and the claimant concur in the`
  line `appointment of a single arbitrator, the Collector on the part of Government, and the claimant, shall each`
  line `appoint an arbitrator. The appointment shall be in writing, and neither of the said parties shall have power`
  line `to revoke the same without the consent of the other.`
  line `Clause 3. — Arbitrator how to be chosen when there are several claimants for compensation. — If`
  line `there be several claimants for compensation in respect to the same injury, and they cannot agree in the`
  line `appointment of an arbitrator on their behalf, in that case each of them may nominate one person; and the`
  line `Collector shall choose by lot out of the person so nominated by the parties, or any of them a person to act`
  line `as arbitrator on behalf of the claimants. If only one person shall be so nominated, he shall be the arbitrator`
  line `on behalf of the claimants.`
  line `Clause 4. — Appointment of third arbitrator. — When more than a single arbitrator shall be appointed,`
  line `the arbitrators shall, before they enter upon the matters referred to them, nominate and appoint by writing`
  line `a third person to act with them as arbitrator; and in case the arbitrators shall neglect to appoint such third`
  line `arbitrator for a period of seven day s after having been required so to do, the Collector may appoint such`
  line `third arbitrator. If the arbitrators differ in opinion, or if one of them, having received due notice of a meeting`
  line `of arbitrators, neglect to attend, any two arbitrators may make an awar d.`
  line `Clause 5. — Arbitrator refusing or becoming incapable to act, &c. — If any person, on being`
  line `appointed an arbitrator, shall refuse to act, or after accepting the appointment, shall die or become incapable`
  line `of acting, another person shall be appointed in his stead, in the same manner in which the first person was`
  line appointed.
  line `Clause 6. — Collector empowered to enforce attendance of arbitrators. — After the arbitrators have`
  line `accepted the appointment, the Collector shall be competent to exercise towards them such powers and`
  line `authority, for securing their attendance and the due completion of their award, as the said Collector may`
  line `legally exercise towar ds witness summoned before him, when acting judicially for the purposes of`
  line `compelling them to attend and give evidence.`
  line `Clause 7. — In default of award within a specified period, fresh arbitrators may be chosen. — If no`
  line `award to made within a period to be fixed for that purpose by the Collector, he may order that the matter`
  line `shall be referred to another arbitrator or other arbitrators, to be chosen in the same manner and subject to`
  line `the same rules as the first.`
  line `Clause 8. — Collector to furnish information to the arbitrators, and to enforce the attendance and`
  line `examination of witnesses, &c. — The Collector shall furnish to the arbitrators, or, so far as may be in his`
  line `power, procure for them, any information which his records or those of any public department may afford`
  line `connected with the subject of e nquiry. He shall, on the application of the arbitrators, summon any witnesses`
  line `whom the arbitrators may call for, and whom the parties may not be able to produce before them without`
  line `such process, and require the persons so summoned to bring and produce before them all such books, papers,`
  line `deeds, writings, maps and plans as they shall require. He shall also cause the proper affirmation to be made`
  line `and signed by any witness whom the arbitrators may desire to examine upon aff irmation, or he may`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-4
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `Page 4`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  sourcePage 4
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line 4
  line `empower the arbitrators to cause such affirmation to be made and signed before them. Any witness who`
  line `shall refuse or omit to appear when duly summoned by the Collector, or who shall appear but shall refuse`
  line `to make such affirmation, or who shall refuse to give evidence, shall be liable to the same punishment which`
  line `would be incurred under the law by a witness refusing to appear o r give evidence before the Collector when`
  line `acting judicially. Any person giving intentionally and deliberately a false deposition under an affirmation,`
  line `in any case referred to arbitration as above, shall be held to be guilty of perjury, and shall be liable to the`
  line `penalties prescribed for that offence by law.`
  line `Clause 9. — Award of arbitrators. — On the close of the inquiry the arbitrators shall deliver a full and`
  line `complete award, which shall specify the amount of compensation and the party or parties entitled thereto.`
  line `The proceedings of the arbitration shall be deposited in the Collector's office; and every party interested`
  line `therein shall be entitled to a copy of the award on plain paper under the seal and signature of the Collector,`
  line `which copy shall be prima facie evidence thereof.`
  line `Clause 10. — P ayment of compensation may in certain cases be deferred. — If the right to the`
  line `compensation awarded shall in any case be doubtful, or if there exists any ground which, in the judgement`
  line `of the arbitrators or of the Collector, render it improper to make immediate payment thereof to any of the`
  line `claimants, the amount shall be invested in Government securities, and held in deposit until one of the`
  line `claimants shall obtain an order of Court for the payment thereof.`
  line `Clause 11. — Reversal or alteration of award. — No award passed under this S ection shall be liable`
  line `to be reversed or altered, except by the decision of a Civil Court on the ground of corruption or misconduct`
  line `of the arbitrators and no suit to set aside such an award shall be entertained, unless it be instituted within`
  line `three months from the date of the a ward. In case the award shall be reversed, the matter shall be referred to`
  line `another arbitrator or other arbitrators, to be appointed in the same manner as the first.`
  line `Clause 12. — Suits and proceedings against Government, except suits for reversal of awards, to be`
  line `dismissed with cost. — All suits and proceedings instituted against Government in any case in which`
  line `compensation has been awarded, except suits instituted for the reversal of awards as aforesaid, shall be`
  line `dismissed with costs. Proviso. - But nothing herein contained shall affect the right of any party to recover`
  line `the amount awarded from any person who may have received the same without any just title thereto.`
  line `Clause 13. — Estimated value of benefit to be set off against compensation to be awarded. — In fixing`
  line `the amount of compensation to which any person may be entitled by reason of any of the acts mentioned in`
  line `Clause 1 of this S ection, the Court or arbitrators, as the case may be, shall take into consideration whether`
  line `any party to the suit or arbitration has derived or will derive, benefit from the act in respect of which the`
  line `compensation is claimed, and shall set off the estimated value of such benefit, if any, against the`
  line `compensation which would otherwise be decreed or awarded to that party.`
  line `Clause 14. — The provisions of this Section not to apply to cases of compensation in respect to huts,`
  line `trees, or crops. — The provisions of this S ection shall not be held applicable to cases in which the`
  line `compensation to be made has reference only to huts, trees, or crops, which it may be necessary to remove`
  line `or destroy in enlarging or changing the line of a public embankment. In all such cases the officer in charge`
  line `of the public embankmen ts of the district shall report to the Collector, and the Collector shall thereupon`
  line `proceed to value and make compensation for such huts, trees and crops, in the manner prescribed in`
  line `Section XII. of this Act.`
  line `VIII. Clause 1. — Application by land - holder to have a sluice made in a public embankment. — If any`
  line `land - holder, farmer, or cultivator be desirous of having a sluice made in any public embankment for the`
  line `purpose of drainage or irrigation, he shall make an application in writi ng to the Collector of the district in`
  line `which such embankment is situate. The application shall contain such particulars of the land to be drained`
  line `or irrigated as may enable the officers of the Crown to judge of the advantage which may be derived from`
  line `the w ork, and shall declare as regards an embankment maintained at the expense of the State, whether the`
  line `applicant is willing to bear such part, not exceeding half of the cost thereof, as may be determined by the`
  line `Provincial Government; and, as regards any other public embankment whether the applicant is willing to`
  line `defray the whole or such part of the cost incidental to and attendant on, the proposed work, as may be`
  line `determined as aforesaid.`
  line `Clause 2. — Officer in immediate charge of embankments to report on the proposed work. — The`
  line `Collector shall transmit such application to the O fficer in charge of the embankments of the district, who`
  line `shall report his opinion thereon to the Superintendent of Embankments, and, if he be of opinion that`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-5
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Page 5`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `compliance with the application is unobjectionable shall annex to his report a plan of the proposed work`
  line `and an estimate of the expense of its construction. The Superintendent of Embankments shall pass such`
  line `order thereon as he shall think fit, which order shall be final.`
  line `Clau se 3. — Upon the applicant engaging to the defray the cost, Collector may issue certificate. — If`
  line `the construction of the proposed sluice receive the approval of the Superintendent of Embankments, the`
  line `Collector shall require the applicant to enter into a writ ten agreement to defray the whole or half of the`
  line `expense or such portion thereof as may be determined under the provisions of Clause 1 of this section, as`
  line `the case may be, and, upon such agreement being executed, shall issue a certificate to the officer in charge`
  line `of the public embankments of the district to construct the sluice.`
  line `IX. Opening of sluices. — Sluices constructed in any public embankment shall be opened only by, or`
  line `with the permission of the officer of the immediate charge of the embankment, under such orders, either`
  line `general or special, as he may receive from the officer in charge of public embankments of the district or`
  line `from the Superintendent of Embankments.`
  line `X. Officer in immediate charge of embankments may authori z e temporary water - course, &c. to`
  line `be made. — Whenever any person is desirous that a temporary watercourse should be made through, or`
  line `that a temporary roadway should be made over any public embankment, or that a temporary dam should be`
  line `constructed in any embanked river, he shall appl y to the nearest officer of the Embankment Department,`
  line `who shall communicate the application to the officer in charge of the public embankments of the district,`
  line `and that officer shall pass such orders thereon as he shall think fit, subject to the control o f the`
  line `Superintendent of Embankments. If the proposed work is to be executed by an officer of the Crown the`
  line `applicant, before the commencement of the work, shall enter into a written agreement to defray the expenses`
  line `of, and incidental to, making such roadway, or of making and closing or removing such watercourse or`
  line `dam. In any case of emergency the officer in immediate charge of an embankment, subject to such general`
  line `instructions as he may receive from the officer in charge of the embankments of the di strict, or from the`
  line `Superintendent of Embankments, may cause a temporary watercourse to be made through such`
  line embankment.
  line `XI. Clause 1. S pecifications and estimates for maintaining or improving embankments kept up at`
  line `the expense of zamindars to be prepared annually, &c. — Specifications of the work and estimates of the`
  line `expense which may be required for the maintenance or improvement of embankments kept up at the expense`
  line `of zamindars or others shall be prepared as soon after the rains in each year as may be practicable. Copies`
  line `of the specifications and estimates shall be transmitted to the office of the Collector, and may be examined`
  line `by any person interested in the embankments. Notice of the receipt of the specifications and estimates shall`
  line `be posted up in th e Collector's office; and, should any objection be preferred by any such person within a`
  line `period of one month from the date of such notice, the Collector shall communicate the objection, with his`
  line `own opinion thereupon, to the Superintendent of Embankments, who shall pass such orders as may appear`
  line `to him reasonable and proper: Provided, however, that if the objection referred to the construction of sluices`
  line `or other new works, any person dissatisfied with the order of the Superintendent may appeal to the`
  line `Com missioner, who, subject to the orders of the Board of Revenue and of the Provincial Government may`
  line `disallow the construction of the work.`
  line `Clause 2. — Accounts to be forwarded to Collector, who may recover the amount as arrears of`
  line `Government revenue. — The accounts of the actual expense incurred in maintaining or improving`
  line `embankments kept up at the expense of zamindars or others and in constructing and repairing sluices and`
  line `making temporary watercourses or roadways through or over any public embankment, or executing any`
  line `other work the expense of which may be chargeable to individuals, shall be prepared as soon as possible`
  line `after the completion of such works, and shall, as soon as such accounts shall have received the sanction of`
  line `the Superintendent of Embankme nts, be forwarded to the office of the Collector, and may be there examined`
  line `by any person interested. Notice of the receipt of the accounts shall be posted up in the Collector's office;`
  line `and if, within one month from the date of such notice, any interested person shall object to the accounts, on`
  line `the ground either that the work charged for has not been performed, or that the whole sum charged has not`
  line `been expanded, or that the rates of charge are higher than the estimate, the Collector shall inquire into such`
  line `objection, and if the objection appears to be well founded, shall communicate the same with his opinion`
  line `thereon, to the Superintendent of Embankments. If the Superintendent concurs with the Collector, he shall`
  line `pass order accordingly; if he differs, the ca se shall be reported to the Commissioner whose decision shall`
  line `be final. When the objection shall have been finally disposed of, or, if no objection be preferred when a full`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
