obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `month shall have elapsed from the date of notice, the Collector shall proceed to le vy the amount from the`
  line `parties liable to pay the same by the process which is or may be in force for the recovery of arrears of`
  line `Government revenue.`
  line `XII. Clause 1. — Superintendent to report to Collector as to removal of buildings, etc. — Whenever`
  line `the Superintendent of Embankments shall be of opinion that the removal of any houses, huts or other`
  line `buildings, situated between a public embankment and the river, is necessary, he shall make a report to that`
  line `effect, accompanied by a detailed stat ement of the houses, huts or other buildings to be removed, to the`
  line `Collector of the district in whose jurisdiction the land on which such houses, huts or other buildings stand,`
  line `is situated.`
  line `Clause 2. — Collector to give notice to claimants. — When such report is received the Collector shall`
  line `cause a notice, containing a general description of the houses, huts or other buildings proposed to be`
  line `removed, to be affixed in some conspicuous place upon the land, and to be published by proclamation in`
  line `the nearest bazar, calling on all persons claiming a right in such houses, huts or other buildings to appear`
  line `in person or by authori z ed agent at a place to be specified in the notice, on or before a given date, not being`
  line `less than fifteen days from the date of such proclamation, in order to make known the amount and particulars`
  line `of their claim to compensation to a jury to be appointed in the following manner.`
  line `Clause 3. — Selection of jury. — The Collector shall direct a Deputy Collector or a Principal Officer`
  line `of his establishment to proceed to the spot, and thereto select three respectable inhabitants of the`
  line `neighbourhood, to form with himself, a jury for determine the value of the houses, hut s or buildings, and,`
  line `if any dispute should arise, the rights of the claimants.`
  line `Clause 4. — Proceedings of jury. — The jury shall assess the value of each house, hut or building`
  line `separately. If in any case they differ, the value shall be assessed according to the opinion of the majority;`
  line `and, if they be equally divided, the Deputy Collector or other officer as aforesaid shall have a casting vote.`
  line `Clause 5. — Award of jury. — Having completed their proceedings, the jury shall make their award,`
  line `which shall contain a schedule of the houses, huts and buildings, the amount of value assessed on each and`
  line `the name of the person or persons entitled to receive the same. The award shall be final and conc lusive and`
  line `not open to question in the Civil Court: Provided always that any person who was not present at the inquiry,`
  line `or whose claim may have been set aside by the jury, may institute a suit for the value of the property claimed`
  line `by him against the perso n to whom payment may have been made under the award.`
  line `XIII. After award, Collector to give notice of payment, and to remove buildings, & c. in 30 days. —`
  line `The Collector, on receiving the award, shall cause a notice to be affixed in some conspicuous place upon`
  line `the land, with a citation calling on the parties to appear before him or the Deputy Collector or other officer`
  line `aforesaid, in person or by authorised a gent, at a certain time and place, and receive the amount so awarded,`
  line `and warning them to remove their houses, huts or other buildings within thirty days from the date of such`
  line notice.
  line `XIV. Collector may remove buildings, &c., at the cost of the owners, in case they neglect to do so`
  line `themselves. — If, on the expiration of the above stated period, the houses, huts, or other buildings shall`
  line `have not been previously removed, the Collector shall cause the same to be removed or levelled; and if any`
  line `expense be incu rred in removing or levelling the same, the Collector may sell the materials at public auction`
  line `in order to defray the charge, delivering any surplus that may remain to the owner.`
  line `XV. Penalty for obstructing officer or person in discharge of duty. — Whoever wilfully obstructs`
  line `any duly authorised person in removing or levelling any embankment, house, hut or other building shall be`
  line `liable to be imprisoned for any time not exceeding six months, with or without labour, at the discretion of`
  line `the Magistrate, or to fine not exceeding two hundred rupees, commutable, if not paid, to a period of`
  line `imprisonment not exceeding six months, or to both.`
  line `XVI. Penalty for wilful damage to embankment by cutting, etc. — Whoever wilfully, and without`
  line `due authority cut s through, or attempts to cut through, any embankment, whether public or private, or`
  line `destroys, or attempts to destroy, any such embankment, or open any sluice or water - course in any such`
  line `embankment, shall be liable, on conviction before a Magistrate, to be imprisoned for a term not exceeding`
  line `one year, with or without labour, or to a fine not exceeding two hundred rupees, commutable, if not paid,`
  line `to a period of imprisonment not exceeding one year, or to both; or, if the Magistrate be of opinion that such`
  line `pun ishment is insufficient for the offence, he may commit the offender to the Sessions Court, in which case`
